[{"id":"VR866838","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a disk with a radius of R on top of a rectangular prism. A small cylinder is on the disk at a distance of the fraction R over 2 from the center of the disk. An arrow indicates that the disk rotates counterclockwise about a vertical axis through its center.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR866838.g02.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A thin disk of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, and rotational inertia <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"I equals, one half M times R squared\"><math alttext=\"I equals, one half M times R squared\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span> can rotate about a vertical axis through its center, as shown in the figure. A small cylinder, also of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, sits on the disk at a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one half R\"><math alttext=\"one half R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> from the center. A motor (not shown) can spin the disk about its center.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Both objects are initially at rest when the motor is turned on at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>. The angular speed of the cylinder is described by the function <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega equals, omega sub f, end sub, times, open parenthesis, 1 minus, e raised to the negative of the fraction lowercase t over uppercase T, power, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"omega equals, omega sub f, end sub, times, open parenthesis, 1 minus, e raised to the negative of the fraction lowercase t over uppercase T, power, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ω</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mi>t</mi><mi>T</mi></mfrac></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span> for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t greater than or equal to 0\"><math alttext=\"t greater than or equal to 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega sub f\"><math alttext=\"omega sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ω</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase T\"><math alttext=\"uppercase T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>T</mi></math></span></span> are positive constants. The cylinder does not slide relative to the surface of the disk as the disk rotates.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">For the following questions, express all algebraic answers in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega sub f\"><math alttext=\"omega sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ω</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase T\"><math alttext=\"uppercase T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>T</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:Ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ai\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a)</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the maximum net torque exerted on the cylinder-disk system about the disk’s center.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR866838_rubric"},{"id":"VR866838","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aii\"><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. Consider the frictional force that acts on the cylinder at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t, equals uppercase T\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t, equals uppercase T\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi></math></span></span>. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> whether this force has a tangential component only, a radial component only, or both tangential and radial components. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR866838_rubric"},{"id":"VR866838","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the magnitude of the <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">linear</span> acceleration of the cylinder at the instant when the angular speed of the disk is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction with numerator omega sub f, and denominator 3\"><math alttext=\"the fraction with numerator omega sub f, and denominator 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><msub><mi>ω</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR866838_rubric"}]